
# tech_notes series  

##############
##  VSCODE  ##
##############

Settings:
    # Font Size: 20
    # Wordrap: on
    # Terminal Integrated Fontsize: 20
    # Terminal Shell for Windows: "C:\\Program Files\\Git\\bin\\bash.exe"
    # Color Theme: High Contrast



Key Shortcuts
    # F1 - Command Pallette
    #  


VSCode Packages required:
    # Remote - WSL extension
    # 


Integrated Terminal
    # View > Integrated Terminal (Ctrl + `)
    # Press "+" and add a new bash shell
        # you can add multiple bash shells
        # you can delete shells using "bucket" icon

Features:
    # Dig function further:
        # Right-click > Go Definition
        # Right-click > Peek Definition
    # To edit an item's occurances:
        # Right-click > Change all occurances
    # Copy/cut/move:
        # Shift+Alt+Up/Down
        # Ctrl+X/C/V with no highlighting
    

Extensions:
    # Bracket Pair Colorizer
    # Live Server Ritwick Dey 
    # vscode-icons
    # vscode-faker
    # Javascript ES6 Code Snippets
    # Vue2 Snippets
    # Python 4M
    # ayu
    # pylint
    
    
Version Control:
    # click git repo icon to intialize
    # U - unstaged/untracked
    # RightClick > Stage/Unstage
    # Three dots next to the repo ...
    
Debugger:
    1. click debugger icon >|<
    2. Set a breaking point (red circle)
    3. Click on launch.json gear icon
    4. Select debug config code env (Python, Django, etc.)
    5. Click Start Debugging (green triangle)
        NOTE: In launch.json, you might need to set the following:
            "justMyCode": false
    6. Add Watchers as you need
        # better than print statements :))
    7. Also check out "debug console"

Testing:
    1. Open test_*.py files
    2. Go to F1 > Python: Discover Tests
    3. Enable and Config Test Framework
    4. Select framework > unittest
    5. The location of the test files: Root folder?
    6. Test Files Naming Pattern: test_*.py
    7. Notice Run|Debug Tests links
    8. Check:
        > the bottom test bar
        > OUTPUT pane (Terminal)
        > Tests pane (Lab icon)
    9. Make sure the test files are under PATH??

       




    

